<script>
const L=['a','b','c','d'];
const Q=[
  {id:1,yr:'2023',topic:'PLI & Export Share',
   text:'Consider the following statements: [2023]\nStatement-I: India accounts for 3.2% of global export of goods.\nStatement-II: Many local companies and some foreign companies operating in India have taken advantage of India\'s Production-linked Incentive (PLI) scheme.\n\nWhich one of the following is correct?',
   opts:['Both Statements correct; Statement-II explains Statement-I','Both Statements correct; Statement-II does NOT explain Statement-I','Statement-I correct but Statement-II incorrect','Statement-I incorrect but Statement-II correct'],
   ans:3,
   exp:'Statement-I is INCORRECT — India\'s share of global merchandise exports is around 1.8–2%, NOT 3.2%. India has been consistently trying to increase this share but has not yet reached 3.2%. Statement-II is CORRECT — The PLI scheme has attracted both domestic and foreign companies across sectors like electronics, pharmaceuticals, textiles, etc. Since Statement-I is wrong and Statement-II is correct, option (d) is the answer.'},

  {id:2,yr:'2020',topic:'Bilateral Trade – South Asia',
   text:'Consider the following statements: [2020]\n1. The value of Indo-Sri Lanka trade has consistently increased in the last decade.\n2. "Textile and textile articles" constitute an important item of trade between India and Bangladesh.\n3. In the last five years, Nepal has been the largest trading partner of India in South Asia.\n\nWhich is/are correct?',
   opts:['1 and 2 only','2 only','3 only','1, 2 and 3'],
   ans:1,
   exp:'Statement 1: WRONG — Indo-Sri Lanka trade has NOT consistently increased; it has fluctuated due to political tensions, COVID, and Sri Lanka\'s economic crisis. Statement 2: CORRECT — Textiles and textile articles (garments, yarn, fabrics) are indeed a significant trade category between India and Bangladesh. Bangladesh is a major garment exporter and imports raw materials/yarn from India. Statement 3: WRONG — Bangladesh, not Nepal, is generally India\'s largest trading partner in South Asia. Only Statement 2 is correct.'},

  {id:3,yr:'2020',topic:'International Trade – India',
   text:'With reference to international trade of India, which is/are correct? [2020]\n1. India\'s merchandise exports are less than merchandise imports.\n2. India\'s imports of iron & steel, chemicals, fertilisers and machinery have decreased.\n3. India\'s exports of services are more than its imports of services.\n4. India suffers from an overall trade/current account deficit.\n\n[* This question was dropped by UPSC]',
   opts:['1 and 2 only','2 and 4 only','3 only','1, 3 and 4 only'],
   ans:3,
   exp:'[Note: This question was officially DROPPED by UPSC.] Statement 1: CORRECT — India consistently imports more goods than it exports (trade deficit). Statement 2: INCORRECT — India\'s imports of these industrial goods have generally increased, not decreased. Statement 3: CORRECT — India is a net exporter of services (IT, BPO, finance, travel), exporting far more services than it imports. Statement 4: CORRECT — India runs a persistent current account deficit (trade + services + transfers). Statements 1, 3, and 4 are correct.'},

  {id:4,yr:'2020',topic:'WTO – TRIMS',
   text:'With reference to Trade-Related Investment Measures (TRIMS), which is/are correct? [2020]\n1. Quantitative restrictions on imports by foreign investors are prohibited.\n2. They apply to investment measures related to trade in both goods and services.\n3. They are not concerned with the regulation of foreign investment.\n\nSelect the correct answer:',
   opts:['1 and 2 only','2 only','1 and 3 only','1, 2 and 3'],
   ans:2,
   exp:'Statement 1: CORRECT — TRIMs prohibit investment measures that impose quantitative restrictions on imports or exports (e.g., local content requirements, trade balancing requirements). Statement 2: INCORRECT — The WTO Agreement on TRIMs applies only to trade in GOODS, not services (services are covered separately under GATS). Statement 3: CORRECT — TRIMs does not regulate FDI itself; it only restricts certain trade-distorting investment measures that relate to goods trade. So Statements 1 and 3 are correct.'},

  {id:5,yr:'2019',topic:'Agricultural Imports',
   text:'Among the agricultural commodities imported by India, which one accounts for the highest imports in terms of value in the last five years? [2019]',
   opts:['Spices','Fresh fruits','Pulses','Vegetable oils'],
   ans:3,
   exp:'Vegetable oils (palm oil, soybean oil, sunflower oil) consistently account for the highest agricultural import bill for India in terms of value. India imports around 14-16 million tonnes of edible oils annually, primarily palm oil from Indonesia and Malaysia, and soybean oil from Argentina and Brazil. The vegetable oil import bill often exceeds ₹75,000–80,000 crore annually, making it far larger than pulses, fruits, or spices imports.'},

  {id:6,yr:'2018',topic:'Edible Oil Imports',
   text:'Consider the following statements: [2018]\n1. The quantity of imported edible oil is more than the domestic production of edible oils in the last five years.\n2. The Government does not impose any custom duty on all the imported edible oils as a special case.\n\nWhich is/are correct?',
   opts:['1 only','2 only','Both 1 and 2','Neither 1 nor 2'],
   ans:0,
   exp:'Statement 1: CORRECT — India imports approximately 14–16 million tonnes of edible oils per year, which exceeds domestic production of around 8–10 million tonnes. India meets nearly 60–65% of its edible oil needs through imports (primarily palm oil). Statement 2: INCORRECT — India DOES impose customs duty on imported edible oils. In fact, the government has periodically reduced customs duty to manage domestic prices, but a zero-duty exemption for ALL edible oils has not been the policy. Duties vary by type of oil. Only Statement 1 is correct.'},

  {id:7,yr:'2006',topic:'Export Growth & WTO Share',
   text:'Consider the following statements: [2006]\n1. During financial year 2004-05, an increase of below 10% over export value (in rupee terms) compared to 2003-04 was reported.\n2. According to WTO, India\'s share in world merchandise exports was 2% in 2005.\n\nWhich is/are correct?',
